\f0\fs51\fsmilli25995 \cf2 1 | The Human Body and Its Systems
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students explore the human body as a collection of working systems. We explain\
that the body has many parts (such as bones, muscles, heart, lungs, brain and stomach) that\
each belong to a system with a special role. These systems must cooperate. For example,\
bones and muscles work together so we can stand and walk; the heart and blood vessels work\
with the lungs so cells get oxygen; and nerves from the brain communicate with all parts of the\
body. This overview introduces the names of major systems (skeletal, muscular, circulatory,\
respiratory, etc.) and shows that health depends on all systems working in harmony.\
After this lesson, students will understand that the body is organized into different systems, and\
they can name the main systems and their jobs. They will know that organs (like the heart or\
brain) are part of these systems and that systems collaborate to keep us alive and healthy.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 1 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 1: The Human Body and Its Systems\
The human body is made of many parts (bones, muscles, heart, lungs, brain, stomach, etc.),\
each in a system with a special role. These systems must work together. Each system (like\
skeletal, muscular, circulatory, respiratory, nervous) has a main job, and health depends on\
them cooperating.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
Name one system in the body and its main function.\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why is it important that body systems work together?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Give an example of two systems collaborating (e.g. running requires which systems?).\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Major body systems include skeletal (bones), muscular (muscles), circulatory\
(heart/vessels), respiratory (lungs), nervous (brain/nerves), digestive, and others.\
Bones (skeletal) and muscles (muscular) work together: bones provide shape/support\
and protect organs, while muscles pull on bones to move. For example, the ribcage\
(bones) shields the heart and lungs.\
The heart and blood vessels (circulatory system) work with the lungs (respiratory\
system) to pump oxygenated blood to every cell. The brain and nerves (nervous system)\
send messages between the brain and body parts.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
If the heart stopped working, how would that affect other systems?\
Which system carries oxygen to cells? Which removes carbon dioxide?\
How do bones, muscles, and nerves work together to let you pick up a ball and throw it?\
More to Learn:\
Organs are parts of systems (e.g. heart is an organ of the circulatory system, lungs are organs\
of the respiratory system, brain of the nervous system). Each organ is made of tissues of cells.\
Cells form tissues, tissues form organs, and organs form systems.Keeping all systems healthy (through nutrition, exercise, rest) ensures the whole body works\
well.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
Give an example of an organ and the system it belongs to.\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why must your respiratory and circulatory systems work together when you exercise?\
\uc0\u9679 \
How does the skeletal system help the muscular system in movement?
