\fs51\fsmilli25995 2 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 2: Cells \'96 The Building Blocks of Life\
Cells are the tiny units of life in our bodies; they are the basic building blocks of the body. Every\
tissue and organ is made of many cells. Cells are so small we need a microscope to see them,\
but our body has trillions. Each cell has a job (e.g. muscle cells help us move, nerve cells send\
signals). Cells can divide to make new cells, which helps us grow and heal.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
What is a cell? Can you name one type of cell?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why do you think cells multiply when we grow?\
\uc0\u9679 \
How would you explain \'93building block\'94 when talking about cells?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Cells are tiny but numerous: the body contains trillions of cells. Each type of cell has a\
function (muscle cells contract for movement, nerve cells send messages). Groups of\
similar cells form tissues.\
When we eat and play, cells need to divide to grow new tissue and replace old or injured\
cells. Cell division copies the cell\'92s genes so the new cell is like the original.\
Cells organize life: many similar cells make a tissue, and different tissues combine to\
make an organ. For example, heart muscle cells form cardiac tissue, and cardiac tissue\
(with other tissue types) makes the heart organ.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Why can\'92t we see cells without a microscope? How do we know they exist?\
What happens to your muscles if the muscle cells could not divide?\
Can you describe the path from a cell to a tissue to an organ (choose any organ)?\
More to Learn:\
Cells keep tissues healthy. Healthy muscle tissue comes from healthy muscle cells working\
together. If cells multiply healthily, organs grow and work well.\
Remember: cells \uc0\u8594  tissues \u8594  organs \u8594  systems. This pattern repeats at each level of our\
body\'92s organization.Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
What is an example of two different tissues working together in one organ?\
\uc0\u9679 \
How does cell division help a scraped knee heal?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why is it important that cells accurately copy their DNA when they divide?
\fs51\fsmilli25995 3 | Tissues and Organs
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Building on cells, this lesson explains tissues and organs. Students will learn that tissue is a\
group of similar cells working together, and an organ is made of several tissues. For example,\
muscle tissue in your arm is made of muscle cells, and your stomach is an organ made of\
muscle tissue plus other tissue types. We can use the example: skin is an organ made mainly of\
skin cells (a tissue), and the heart is an organ made of heart muscle tissue and other tissues.\
This lesson helps students see the big picture: cells build tissues, tissues form organs, and\
organs make systems.\
After this lesson, students will be able to explain that similar cells form tissues, and different\
tissues together make up an organ. They will know examples of organs (like brain, stomach,\
skin) and recognize that each organ has many tissues (for instance, muscle and nerve tissues\
in the heart and brain). This reinforces the idea that cells are organized into higher levels\
(tissues and organs) in the body.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 3 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 3: Tissues and Organs\
Tissues are groups of similar cells working together, and organs are made of two or more tissue\
types. For example, muscle tissue is made of muscle cells, and your stomach is an organ made\
of muscle tissue plus other tissues. Groups of cells make tissues, and groups of tissues form\
organs. This shows that cells build tissues, tissues make organs, and organs make systems.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
What is a tissue? What is an organ? How are they different?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Name an organ in your body and guess what tissues it might have.\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why do you think tissues and organs are important for the body?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
A tissue is a group of similar cells doing a job. For example, muscle tissue is many\
muscle cells working together. Skin tissue is many skin cells joined in layers.\
An organ is made of different tissues. For example, the heart is an organ with muscle\
tissue (to pump), nerve tissue (to regulate heartbeat), and blood vessel tissue (to carry\
blood). The stomach organ has muscle tissue (to churn food) and lining tissue (to protect\
and digest).\
Think of a house: cells are like bricks, tissues are like walls, and organs are like rooms.\
Each level builds on the smaller ones.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
What tissue types do you think are in your heart? (e.g. muscle for pumping)\
How does skin show both tissue and organ levels (hint: skin itself is an organ)?\
Can two different organs share a tissue type? (Hint: muscle tissue is in your heart and in\
muscles in legs.)\
More to Learn:\
Examples: Skin is an organ made mostly of skin cells (epidermis tissue) and inner skin layers.\
The stomach is an organ made of muscle tissue (to move food), inner lining tissue (for digestive\
juices), and connective tissues.Recognizing that cells \uc0\u8594  tissue \u8594  organ helps us understand the body\'92s structure.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Describe the layers (tissyes) you would find in a tooth (hint: enamel is one tissue).\
How do tissues help an organ perform its function (e.g., stomach tissues digest food)?\
Why is it helpful that tissues are made of similar cells?
\fs51\fsmilli25995 4 | Skeletal System \'96 Bones and Joints
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, learners study the skeletal system. We describe that the skeleton is the body\'92s\
support framework of hard, strong bones. Children learn that humans have more than 200\
bones in their bodies. These bones give the body shape and protect soft organs (for example,\
the ribcage shields the heart and lungs). We explain how bones connect at joints (like knees\
and elbows) and how a joint allows movement (like a hinge or ball-socket). Students also hear\
that bones store minerals (like calcium) and contain bone marrow where blood cells are made.\
Overall, this lesson shows how the skeleton provides structure, protection, and support for\
movement.\
By the end of the lesson, students will know that bones form a sturdy framework for the body.\
They will remember that the skeleton supports the body and protects organs. They will be able\
to name examples of bones (skull, ribs, femur) and joints (elbow, knee), and explain that\
together bones and joints let us stand upright, move, and keep the body protected.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 4 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 4: Skeletal System \'96 Bones and Joints\
The skeletal system is the body\'92s support framework made of bones and joints. The human\
skeleton has about 206 bones in adults. These hard bones give the body shape and protect soft\
organs (for example, the ribcage shields the heart and lungs). Joints (like knees and elbows)\
are places where two bones meet and allow movement (hinge joints like knees flex,\
ball-and-socket joints like hips rotate). Bones also store minerals like calcium and contain bone\
marrow, where blood cells are made.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
About how many bones do you think an adult human has?\
\uc0\u9679 \
What do bones do for your body?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Can you point to a joint on your body (like knee or elbow)? What does it do?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
The skeleton provides a sturdy framework for the body. Bones support your weight and\
give you your shape. For example, the spine keeps you upright and the skull (head\
bone) protects the brain.\
Bones protect soft organs. Ribs protect the heart and lungs; the skull protects the brain;\
the pelvis protects parts of the digestive and reproductive systems.\
Bones meet at joints, which allow movement. For instance, elbow and knee are hinge\
joints that bend. Shoulder and hip are ball-socket joints that move in all directions.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Name two bones that protect vital organs and the organ they protect.\
How does the skeleton help you stand up and move?\
What might happen if you didn\'92t have knees or elbows?\
More to Learn:\
Bones have additional roles: they store minerals (like calcium and phosphorus) which\
strengthen bones, and bone marrow (inside some bones) makes new blood cells.Examples: Femur (thigh bone) is the longest bone, helping us walk; the ribs form the ribcage\
protecting chest organs.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
What minerals do your bones store and why are they important?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why do children\'92s bones grow stronger when they get enough calcium?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why might a doctor send you for an X-ray when you break a bone? (Hint: imaging, see\
below)
\fs51\fsmilli25995 5 | Muscular System \'96 Muscles and\
Movement
\fs21\fsmilli10995 This lesson covers the muscular system and how muscles move our bodies. We explain that\
muscles are tissues that can contract (tighten) to pull on bones and create movement. Every\
arm, leg, and body part has muscles. The lesson notes that muscles not only move limbs but\
also perform other jobs: for example, the heart itself is a muscle that pumps blood, and smooth\
muscles in the stomach and intestines help digest food. We introduce the idea that people have\
different types of muscle (skeletal muscle for moving bones, cardiac muscle for the heart,\
smooth muscle in organs), but focus on the common idea that muscles provide movement.\
After this lesson, learners will understand that muscles attach to bones and make motion\
possible. They will know that muscle groups in arms and legs let us walk, run and lift. They will\
also recall that there are special muscles like the heart (cardiac muscle) and muscles in\
digestion. They can describe how a muscle contracts to bend an arm or how the heart muscle\
pumps blood, using the basic concept of muscle power.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 5 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 5: Muscular System \'96 Muscles and Movement\
The muscular system consists of tissues (muscles) that can contract (tighten) to move bones\
and parts of the body. When muscles contract, they pull on bones at joints to create motion. For\
example, the muscles in your legs and arms let you run, jump, and lift things. Muscles do more\
than move limbs: the heart itself is a muscle (cardiac muscle) that pumps blood, and smooth\
muscles in organs (like the stomach and intestines) help move food along.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why is the heart called a muscle? What does it do?\
\uc0\u9679 \
What do you do with your muscles when you run or lift something?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Can you name one voluntary muscle (you control) and one involuntary muscle (you don\'92t\
have to think about controlling)?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Skeletal muscles attach to bones and pull on them to create voluntary movement. When\
you decide to move, your brain tells a muscle to contract, which causes your arm to lift\
or your leg to step forward.\
Muscle activity produces heat. When muscles work hard (exercise), your body warms\
up. Muscles also help maintain posture and protect internal organs.\
There are three types of muscle: skeletal (attached to bones, under conscious control),\
cardiac (the heart, works automatically), and smooth (in organs like stomach, intestines,\
blood vessels, work automatically). For example, the heart\'92s muscle (cardiac) pumps\
blood; smooth muscles in your stomach mix food.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
How do muscles work with bones to bend your arm?\
What happens to your muscles when you eat a heavy meal (hint: smooth muscles in\
stomach)?\
Name one activity that uses smooth muscles (heart pumping, or stomach churning).More to Learn:\
Muscles work in groups: to bend an arm, the biceps muscle contracts while the triceps relaxes.\
When you run, muscles in your legs contract in sequence to make stepping possible.\
Exercise helps muscles grow stronger and more efficient. Keeping muscles healthy (through\
activity and proper nutrition) helps all movement.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why do marathon runners have strong leg muscles?\
\uc0\u9679 \
How does muscle activity help keep us warm?\
\uc0\u9679 \
What would happen if you couldn\'92t control your skeletal muscles (for example, you\
couldn\'92t think about lifting your arm)?
\fs51\fsmilli25995 6 | Nervous System \'96 Brain and Nerves
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students explore the nervous system, including the brain, spinal cord, and nerves.\
We explain that nerves carry information and instructions between the brain and the rest of the\
body. For example, nerves send sensory information (like sights or sounds) to the brain, and the\
brain sends back instructions to muscles. The lesson highlights that the brain is the control\
center: it receives signals (what we see, hear, feel) and decides responses (move a hand, talk,\
think). We also mention that nerve cells (neurons) are the building blocks of the nervous system.\
The lesson introduces basic terms like \'93brain\'94 and \'93nerve,\
\'94 and shows how the brain and spinal\
cord are central parts of the system.\
After this lesson, learners will know that the brain and nerves together make the nervous\
system. They will be able to say that nerves carry signals (messages) to the brain and from the\
brain. They will understand that the brain interprets sensory input and controls muscles and\
actions. In summary, students will grasp that the nervous system allows us to sense the world\
and control our bodies.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 6 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 6: Nervous System \'96 Brain and Nerves\
The nervous system is made of the brain, spinal cord, and nerves throughout the body. The\
brain is the control center: it receives information from your senses (eyes, ears, etc.) and sends\
out instructions. Nerves carry information between the brain and body. For example, nerves\
send sensory signals (like touch or sound) to the brain, and the brain sends motor signals back\
to muscles. In short, the nervous system lets you sense the world and move or react.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
What does your brain do when you touch something hot?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Which part of your body do you use to think?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Can you name one nerve (like the spinal cord) and what it does?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Central parts: the brain and spinal cord; peripheral parts: all the nerves branching out.\
Nerves act like wires transmitting signals. For example, if you step on a sharp object,\
sensory nerves send a \'93pain\'94 message to your brain.\
Sensory nerves carry information (what you see, hear, feel) to the brain, and motor\
nerves carry instructions from the brain to muscles. The brain processes input and\
decides actions (like moving a hand).\
This system is how you can see, hear, speak, think, and react to things instantly. Without\
it, the body wouldn\'92t know what\'92s happening or how to respond.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
What might happen if nerves in your arm were cut?\
Why is the spinal cord protected by your backbone?\
How do you blink your eyes when something comes towards you? (Hint: see and react\
via nerves)\
More to Learn:\
Neurons are nerve cells. They connect all parts of the body to the brain, making a network.\
Nerve signals are very fast (like an electrical current).Healthy nervous system: protect your brain (wear helmets), and keep nerves healthy (avoid\
injuries). The brain controls your movements and thoughts, so keeping it well-rested and\
oxygenated is important.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
How do the senses (eyes, ears) and nerves work together to tell your brain about the\
world?\
\uc0\u9679 \
What do you think would happen if your brain couldn\'92t send signals to your legs?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why is sleep important for the brain (hint: processing memory and recovery)?
\fs51\fsmilli25995 7 | Circulatory System \'96 Heart and\
Blood Vessels
\fs21\fsmilli10995 This lesson introduces the circulatory system, focused on the heart and blood vessels. We\
explain that the heart is a pump that pushes blood through a network of blood vessels (arteries\
and veins). The lesson emphasizes that blood carries oxygen and nutrients to every cell and\
carries away waste. For instance, blood circulates nutrients and oxygen and removes wastes.\
We describe how the heart (a muscle) beats to circulate blood: oxygen-rich blood from the lungs\
goes out to the body, and oxygen-poor blood returns to the heart and lungs. We also mention\
the circulatory role in immunity (blood carries infection-fighting cells). Overall, this lesson shows\
how the heart and vessels form a loop that sustains life.\
After the lesson, students will know the heart\'92s function as a pump and the path of blood through\
the body. They should be able to say that blood delivers oxygen and nutrients to cells and\
removes wastes. They will recall that the circulatory system includes the heart plus vessels and\
that it works with the respiratory system to supply oxygen. In short, learners will understand that\
healthy circulation is vital for all body parts.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 7 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 7: Circulatory System \'96 Heart and Blood Vessels\
The circulatory system (cardiovascular system) includes the heart and a network of blood\
vessels (arteries and veins). The heart is a muscle pump that pushes blood through the body.\
Blood carries oxygen and nutrients to every cell and removes wastes like carbon dioxide. In\
each beat, the heart sends oxygen-rich blood (from the lungs) out to the body, and brings\
oxygen-poor blood back to the lungs for more oxygen. The blood also carries immune cells that\
fight germs.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
What organ pumps your blood? What would happen if it stopped?\
\uc0\u9679 \
How does blood travel from the heart to the rest of the body?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why do you feel your pulse or heartbeat when you\'92re excited?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
The heart (a muscle) beats to circulate blood. Arteries carry blood away from the heart\
(usually oxygen-rich), veins carry blood to the heart (often oxygen-poor). Capillaries are\
tiny vessels where exchanges happen.\
Blood delivers oxygen and nutrients (from the digestive system) to cells and picks up\
carbon dioxide and wastes to carry away. This is essential: without blood flow, cells\
would starve and waste would build up.\
The circulatory system works closely with the respiratory system: lungs oxygenate blood,\
then the heart pumps it to body cells. It also helps the immune system by transporting\
white blood cells to fight infections.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Trace one drop of blood: heart \uc0\u8594  lungs \u8594  heart \u8594  body cells \u8594  heart. Name each step.\
What waste does the blood carry away when you exhale?\
How does exercise (like running) affect your heart rate and circulation?\
More to Learn:\
Good heart health: exercise (aerobic) strengthens the heart. For example, jogging or cycling\
improves cardiac endurance.Blood pressure: the pressure of blood on vessel walls; too high pressure can damage vessels,\
so diet and exercise help keep it normal.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why does your heart beat faster when you run?\
\uc0\u9679 \
How is the circulatory system connected to the digestive system? (Hint: after digestion,\
nutrients enter the blood)\
\uc0\u9679 \
Name one way to keep blood vessels healthy (e.g. eating vegetables, avoiding too much\
fat).
\fs51\fsmilli25995 8 | Respiratory System \'96 Lungs and\
Breathing
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, learners study the respiratory system. We explain that breathing brings oxygen\
into the body and removes carbon dioxide. The lungs are described as the key organs: each\
lung is filled with tiny sacs (alveoli) where gas exchange happens. More importantly, the\
respiratory system takes in oxygen and expels carbon dioxide and water. We describe how air\
enters through the nose or mouth, travels down the windpipe into the lungs, and oxygen passes\
into blood while carbon dioxide leaves blood to be exhaled. Students learn that the diaphragm\
(a muscle) helps expand the lungs for breathing. The lesson uses simple terms (lungs, inhale,\
exhale) and emphasizes that cells need oxygen from breathing to produce energy.\
After this lesson, students will know how breathing works. They will be able to explain that lungs\
take in oxygen which enters the blood, and that carbon dioxide is released when we breathe\
out. They should also recall that this oxygen in blood is carried by the circulatory system to all\
cells. In summary, they will understand that respiration (breathing) is how our body gets oxygen\
and removes a waste product, carbon dioxide.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 8 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 8: Respiratory System \'96 Lungs and Breathing\
The respiratory system brings air in and out of the body to exchange gases. Air enters through\
your nose or mouth, goes down the windpipe (trachea) into the lungs. In the lungs, tiny sacs\
called alveoli exchange oxygen and carbon dioxide with the blood. Oxygen from the air moves\
into the blood, and carbon dioxide (a waste gas) moves from blood into the alveoli to be\
exhaled. Breathing happens when the diaphragm (a muscle under the lungs) contracts and\
relaxes, making the lungs expand and release air.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
What muscle do you feel move when you take a deep breath?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Which organ provides oxygen to your blood?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why do you breathe faster when you run or laugh hard?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Lungs are the key organs of the respiratory system. They take in oxygen from the air\
and remove carbon dioxide. Inhaling (breathing in) fills lungs with air; exhaling pushes\
air (with CO
\f2 \uc0\u8322 
\f0 ) out.\
Oxygen in the lungs passes into the bloodstream (via capillaries around alveoli), and\
carbon dioxide in blood passes into the lungs to exit the body.\
The diaphragm muscle controls breathing: when it moves down, lungs expand (inhaling);\
when it moves up, lungs contract (exhaling). We breathe automatically, and cells need\
that oxygen to make energy.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Explain how blood and lungs work together when you breathe out.\
Why do you feel sleepy if you hold your breath (hint: lack of oxygen)?\
What happens to the air you breathe out (carbon dioxide)?\
More to Learn:\
Healthy breathing: keep lungs clear by avoiding smoke and pollutants. Exercise also keeps\
lung capacity strong.Quick fact: we breathe about 12\'9620 times per minute at rest. This ensures a constant supply of\
oxygen.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
How might asthma or a cold affect your breathing?\
Describe why nose breathing (instead of mouth) is helpful (hint: it filters and warms the\
air).\
How do you think lungs and brain work together? (Think about what triggers you to start\
breathing more or less.)
\fs51\fsmilli25995 9 | Digestive System \'96 Food into Energy
\fs21\fsmilli10995 This lesson covers the digestive system and how food becomes fuel. We teach that eating gives\
the body material and energy to grow and work. Since animals need food for energy and growth\
they must change it into a form that the body can use via digestion. We explain the path of food:\
it goes from mouth \uc0\u8594  esophagus \u8594  stomach \u8594  small intestine \u8594  large intestine. At each\
stage, food is broken down: teth chew, stomach acid churns, and intestines use enzymes. We\
mention accessory organs like the liver and pancreas which add digestive juices. The key idea\
