\fs51\fsmilli25995 18 | Vaccines and Antibiotics
\fs21\fsmilli10995 This lesson explains how we defend against germs using medicine. We cover vaccines and\
antibiotics in age-appropriate terms. First, we describe vaccines: harmless forms (dead or\
weakened) of bacteria or viruses are given to the body so the immune system can learn to fight\
them without getting sick. A vaccine shows the immune system a \'93wanted poster\'94 of the germ.\
Next, we discuss antibiotics: medicines that kill bacteria but do not work on viruses. We stress\
that antibiotics should only be used for bacterial infections, under a doctor\'92s care. The lesson\
clarifies why antibiotics won\'92t cure a cold (a virus) and highlights the importance of vaccination\
for prevention.\
After this lesson, students will know that vaccines help the immune system recognize and fight\
future infections. They will also understand that antibiotics are special medicines for bacterial\
infections only. They should remember examples (flu vaccine, chickenpox vaccine) and the idea\
that vaccines have made many diseases rare. In summary, learners will see vaccines and\
antibiotics as medical tools for protection and treatment of illness.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 18 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 18: Vaccines and Antibiotics\
Vaccines and antibiotics are tools doctors use to fight germs. Vaccines prepare the immune\
system to fight future infections without causing disease. A vaccine contains harmless parts of a\
germ (dead or weakened bacteria/virus). This \'93shows\'94 the immune system a germ\'92s \'93wanted\
poster\'94 so it can make antibodies in advance. If the real germ appears later, the immune system\
attacks it quickly. For example, a flu vaccine helps prevent flu. Antibiotics are medicines that kill\
bacteria or stop their growth. They work only on bacteria, not viruses. That\'92s why antibiotics cure\
infections like strep throat but not the common cold (a virus).\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
What is the difference between what vaccines do and what antibiotics do?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Can you name a disease we prevent with a vaccine (e.g. measles, polio)?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why is it important to finish all the antibiotics your doctor gives you?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Vaccines: Introduce dead/weakened germs (or parts) to the body so the immune system\
learns to fight them safely. They create immunity (antibodies) without making you sick.\
For instance, the chickenpox or COVID-19 vaccine trains your body to fight those\
viruses.\
Antibiotics: Drugs specifically for bacterial infections. They either kill bacteria or stop\
them multiplying. They do not affect viruses at all. Doctors prescribe antibiotics for things\
like pneumonia or strep throat, not for colds or flu.\
Using antibiotics correctly is important: only take them for bacterial infections and\
complete the course, so all bacteria are killed and resistance is avoided.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Why doesn\'92t everyone get antibiotics for a virus like the flu?\
How do vaccines help keep diseases like polio rare?\
What could happen if you stop antibiotics early (before feeling better)?More to Learn:\
Safety: Vaccines are tested to be safe. Side effects are usually minor (like a sore arm or mild\
fever). They are one of the best ways to prevent dangerous diseases.\
Hygiene plus medicine: Even with vaccines and antibiotics, handwashing and clean habits help\
prevent germs in the first place.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
Name two vaccines a child might get before entering school.\
\uc0\u9679 \
How do antibiotics know which cells to kill (hint: antibiotics target features only bacteria\
have)\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why shouldn\'92t you share someone else\'92s antibiotics?
\fs51\fsmilli25995 19 | Oral Health \'96 Teeth and Hygiene
\fs21\fsmilli10995 This lesson focuses on teeth, gums, and dental health. We teach that teeth are hard structures\
used for biting and chewing food. Kids learn there are different types of teeth (incisors for\
cutting, molars for grinding, etc.) and that humans have two sets in life (baby teeth and\
permanent teeth). We explain how teeth can get cavities: germs in the mouth form plaque that\
can eat away the tooth enamel, causing holes or cavities. The lesson emphasizes preventive\
habits: brushing teeth, flossing, and visiting the dentist regularly to avoid cavities and gum\
problems. We also mention basic hygiene like not eating too much sugary food. Overall, this\
lesson shows that caring for teeth is an important part of overall health.\
After the lesson, learners will understand that healthy teeth help chew food and should be kept\
clean. They will recall that bacteria in the mouth form a sticky film called plaque which can\
cause cavities. They will know that brushing, flossing, and dentist check-ups are ways to\
prevent these problems. Students should be able to explain why eating sweets and skipping\
brushing can lead to a cavity, summarizing that good oral hygiene keeps teeth and gums\
healthy.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 19 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 19: Oral Health \'96 Teeth and Hygiene\
Teeth are hard structures in your mouth used for biting and chewing food. Humans have\
different types of teeth: incisors (front teeth for cutting), canines (sharp teeth for tearing), and\
molars (back teeth for grinding). We first have baby teeth that fall out, then permanent teeth\
come in. In the mouth, bacteria combine with food particles to form a sticky film called plaque.\
The bacteria in plaque produce acids that can eat away tooth enamel, causing cavities (holes).\
Good habits prevent this: brushing teeth twice a day with fluoride toothpaste, flossing, and\
limiting sugary snacks help remove plaque. Dentists also check and clean teeth to catch\
problems early.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
What are your baby teeth and why do they fall out?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why should you brush your teeth every day?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Can you name a tooth type and what it does (like molars grind food)?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Teeth let us chew food into smaller pieces. Strong enamel (outer coating) protects teeth,\
but it can be damaged by plaque acids. Cavities happen when enamel breaks down.\
Cavities (tooth decay): Bacteria + sugary food form plaque; acids from plaque dissolve\
enamel, forming holes. If untreated, cavities can hurt and lead to infections. Brushing\
and flossing remove plaque before it causes decay.\
Healthy gums and teeth: also floss regularly to clean between teeth, and visit the dentist\
for check-ups and cleanings. Fluoride in toothpaste and water helps strengthen enamel.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
What causes a tooth to have a hole (cavity)?\
How does sugar in drinks affect your teeth?\
Why is fluoride (in toothpaste) good for teeth?\
More to Learn:\
Milk and calcium: Teeth (and bones) need calcium to stay strong. Dairy or fortified alternatives\
supply calcium and vitamin D.Baby teeth are important: they help children chew and talk, and they hold space for adult teeth.\
Protect them too (no sharing utensils with baby teeth).\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why should you not eat candy right before bed?\
\uc0\u9679 \
How does saliva (spit) help protect your teeth?\
\uc0\u9679 \
What do dentists do if a tooth has a big cavity?
\fs51\fsmilli25995 20 | Puberty and Reproductive System
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students explore human reproduction and puberty (with appropriate sensitivity for\
older children). We explain that creating a baby involves a sperm (from a male) and an egg\
(from a female) joining together. Basic anatomy is covered: boys have testes that make sperm;\
girls have ovaries that release eggs. We teach that starting around 10\'9612 years old, bodies go\
through changes called puberty. For girls, this includes one ovary releasing an egg each month\
and menstruation (a monthly cycle). For boys, puberty means their testes start making large\
numbers of sperm daily. The main idea is that boys and girls develop new functions to prepare\
for making babies later.\
After this lesson, learners will know the basic functions of male and female reproductive organs:\
that testes produce sperm and ovaries produce eggs. They will understand that puberty is when\
these systems become active (e.g. girls begin monthly cycles). They should be able to use\
correct terms (sperm, egg, menstruation) and know that fertilization of an egg by a sperm is how\
a pregnancy begins. Overall, students will understand the role of puberty in growth and human\
reproduction.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 20 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 20: Puberty and Reproductive System\
Puberty is the time when the body becomes capable of reproduction. During puberty (around\
ages 10\'9614), many changes happen under the skin. Boys and girls develop sex organs: males\
have testes (in the scrotum) that begin making sperm; females have ovaries (inside the body)\
that release an egg each month. Hormones like estrogen and testosterone cause visible\
changes: voice deepens in boys, facial hair grows, and testes produce sperm daily; girls\
develop breasts, start menstrual periods as an egg is released monthly (menstruation). These\
changes prepare the body for making babies later. It\'92s important to understand these changes\
and stay clean (like taking showers and wearing clean clothes) as the body becomes more\
sensitive.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
Who in your family had body changes when they were around 11\'9613 years old?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Can you name two changes that happen to boys and two changes for girls in puberty?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why is it good to bathe more often during puberty?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Reproductive organs: Males have testes (in scrotum) that produce sperm and hormones;\
females have ovaries that produce eggs. These organs also produce sex hormones\
(testosterone in boys, estrogen in girls).\
Puberty changes: Boys grow facial/body hair, their penis/testes grow, and voice\
deepens. Girls develop breasts, wider hips, and start periods (monthly shedding of the\
uterine lining if no pregnancy). These are normal and natural.\
Reproduction basics: An egg and sperm can join (fertilize) to start a baby\'92s development.\
The fertilized egg implants in the uterus and grows into a baby over nine months.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
What is menstruation and why does it happen in females?\
How often do men\'92s bodies produce sperm (hint: every day after puberty)?\
Why do boys and girls need sex education (to understand these changes and how to\
stay healthy)?More to Learn:\
Privacy and care: During puberty, people often need more privacy and should practice good\
hygiene (daily bathing, deodorant for body odor, menstrual supplies for girls).\
Emotional changes: Puberty also affects emotions and thinking (due to hormones). It\'92s normal to\
feel mood swings or new feelings.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
How does understanding puberty help teenagers?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why is respect and privacy important when discussing these topics?\
\uc0\u9679 \
What is one way to manage mood changes during puberty (e.g., talking to friends,\
exercising)?
\fs51\fsmilli25995 21 | DNA and Heredity
\fs21\fsmilli10995 This lesson introduces DNA, genes, and heredity. We explain that every person\'92s body has a\
set of instructions called DNA, which is packed into chromosomes inside nearly every cell. A\
gene is a section of DNA that carries information for a specific trait. Britannica explains that\
genes are the basic units of heredity and they exist on chromosomes made of DNA. We use\
simple examples: eye color and hair color come from genes. We emphasize that children get\
half of their genes from each parent, which is why they may look like mom or dad. The lesson\
clarifies that not all traits are the same (you might have dad\'92s eyes but mom\'92s hair), because\
each trait is determined by specific genes. We do not go deep into dominant/recessive, but\
highlight that heredity is how characteristics pass down.\
By the end, students will know that genes (made of DNA) carry inherited information. They will\
be able to say that each cell has chromosomes containing genes, and these determine traits\
from parents. They will understand in a broad sense how children resemble their parents\
(sharing gene instructions) but are also unique. This lesson lays the foundation for\
understanding genetics and why families share certain characteristics.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 21 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 21: DNA and Heredity\
DNA is the instruction manual inside cells that carries hereditary information. It is packed into\
chromosomes (thread-like structures) in nearly every cell. Genes are segments of DNA that\
carry information for specific traits (like eye color or hair color). Genes are the basic units of\
heredity that control how we grow and what we look like. We inherit our genes from our parents\
(half from each). That\'92s why children often look like mom or dad. Not all traits are the same: you\
might have your mother\'92s eye color and your father\'92s height. This is because different genes\
control different traits.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why do you have your parents\'92 eye color or hair?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Can you think of a trait that siblings might share with each other (hair color, dimples)?\
\uc0\u9679 \
What is one physical trait you have that you think came from your family?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Every person\'92s DNA is unique, but half of it comes from the mother\'92s egg and half from\
the father\'92s sperm. This mixing of genes makes you related but also unique.\
Genes provide the \'93plan\'94 for all body parts. For example, genes determine whether you\
have brown or blue eyes. They also influence height, blood type, and even some health\
risks.\
Heredity means inherited traits: hair type, eye color, and even things like earlobe shape\
are passed down by genes. Environment and lifestyle also play a role, so you might not\
look exactly like anyone, but genetics set the blueprint.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
What are chromosomes, and where are they found in the cell? (Answer: In the nucleus,\
containing DNA)\
How could two tall parents have a shorter child? (Think about dominant/recessive\
genes)\
Is it possible for siblings to look very different? Why or why not?More to Learn:\
Genetic variation: Everyone\'92s genes are mixed in unique ways, so each person is different.\
Even identical twins have almost the same genes, which is why they look very alike.\
Genetics and health: Some conditions (like some types of diabetes or color blindness) are\
inherited. Knowing family medical history can be important.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
How might genes influence things other than appearance (e.g., how your body works)?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why do family members sometimes share diseases or allergies?\
\uc0\u9679 \
What can someone do if a genetic risk is found in the family (hint: healthy lifestyle,\
check-ups)?
\fs51\fsmilli25995 22 | Hormones and the Endocrine\
System
\fs21\fsmilli10995 This lesson is about hormones, the body\'92s chemical messengers. We explain that hormones are\
chemicals released by glands (like the pituitary, thyroid, pancreas, etc.) and travel through the\
blood to tell cells what to do. Britannica Kids says, Hormones are chemicals that tell cells and\
body parts to do certain things. For example, hormones tell the body when to grow and when to\
stop growing. We introduce examples of hormones: growth hormone (helps children grow),\
insulin (controls blood sugar), arenaline (speeds up heart rate in an emergency), and sex\
hormones (estrogen and testosterone trigger puberty changes). The lesson describes the\
endocrine glands simply and says that hormones help regulate growth, energy use, and other\
processes.\
After this lesson, learners will know that the endocrine system uses hormones to coordinate\
body functions. They will recall that hormones come from glands and that each hormone has\
specific targets (for example, insulin regulates sugar; growth hormone helps muscles grow.\
They will understand that even though hormones work slowly through the blood, they have\
powerful effects on growth and development. In summary, students will see hormones as an\
important part of why the body changes over time (like during puberty) and how it stays in\
balance.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 22 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 22: Hormones and the Endocrine System\
Hormones are chemical messengers in the body. They are produced by glands (called the\
endocrine system) and travel through the blood to organs and cells, telling them what to do.\
Hormones tell cells and body parts to do certain things. For example, insulin (from the\
pancreas) tells body cells to take in sugar; growth hormone (from the pituitary gland) tells the\
body to grow; adrenaline (from adrenal glands) triggers the \'93fight or flight\'94 response (increases\
heart rate). During puberty, sex hormones (estrogen, testosterone) cause the body changes we\
discussed earlier.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
What do you think happens if your body has too much sugar and not enough insulin?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Name a hormone you\'92ve heard of (like insulin) and what it does.\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why is the endocrine system important for growth?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Glands (pituitary, thyroid, pancreas, adrenal, etc.) release hormones into the\
bloodstream. Each hormone has target cells. For example, insulin (pancreas) regulates\
blood sugar. Growth hormone (pituitary) stimulates growth of bones and muscles.\
Thyroid hormones control metabolism (how quickly we use energy).\
Hormones act slower than nerves (circulating in blood), but they have long-lasting\
effects. They regulate growth, metabolism, water balance, and more.\
The endocrine system keeps the body in balance. For instance, after eating, insulin\
lowers blood glucose; if blood sugar drops, another hormone (glucagon) raises it.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Which organ makes insulin? What happens if it doesn\'92t make enough? (Answer:\
pancreas; leads to diabetes)\
How do adrenaline and insulin work differently? (Adrenaline reacts quickly to stress;\
insulin regulates energy use)\
What symptoms might you see if your thyroid gland released too little hormone (hint:\
metabolism slows)?More to Learn:\
Balance: Hormone levels are very carefully controlled by feedback loops. For example, when\
blood sugar rises, insulin is released; when sugar falls, insulin stops.\
Health tip: Problems in hormones can cause conditions (e.g., diabetes from insulin issues,\
hyperthyroidism from too much thyroid hormone). Eating well and seeing doctors helps manage\
them.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why do people with diabetes need insulin injections?\
\uc0\u9679 \
How might someone\'92s energy level be affected if they have too little thyroid hormone?\
\uc0\u9679 \
What effects do sex hormones have on emotions (hint: sometimes mood swings during\
puberty)?
\fs51\fsmilli25995 23 | Hygiene \'96 Keeping Germs Away
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students learn basic hygiene habits that help keep them healthy. We focus on\
simple practices like washing hands with soap and water, covering coughs and sneezes, and\
bathing regularly. We stress that these habits remove or block germs. We explain important\
moments to wash hands: after using the bathroom, before eating, after playing outside or\
petting animals, etc. The lesson also mentions dental care (brushing teeth) and nail/trimming\
hair for cleanliness. We encourage students to make handwashing a habit (adding soap,\
scrubbing thoroughly). This lesson ties in with earlier ones: keeping hands clean helps the\
immune system by not introducing germs into the body.\
Afterward, learners will understand that hygiene is key to preventing illness. They will remember\
that simple actions (washing hands, bathing) remove germs and protect themselves and others.\
They will know when to wash hands and why (to stop colds, flu, stomach bugs). In short,\
students will see good hygiene as an important daily routine that keeps their body\'92s defenses\
strong.
\fs51\fsmilli25995 23 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 23: Hygiene \'96 Keeping Germs Away\
Hygiene means keeping clean to stay healthy. Simple habits like washing hands with soap and\
water are among the best ways to prevent illness. We should wash hands before eating, after\
using the bathroom, and after playing outside or sneezing. Other hygiene practices: bathe or\
shower regularly, brush teeth daily (oral hygiene), and keep nails and clothes clean. Cover\
coughs and sneezes with your elbow or a tissue (to stop spreading germs). Good hygiene\
complements the immune system by reducing the germs that enter the body.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
When is one of the most important times to wash your hands?\
\uc0\u9679 \
How do you cover your mouth or nose when you cough or sneeze?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why should you trim your fingernails or not bite them?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Washing hands removes germs you might have picked up from surfaces or other people.\
Soap, water, and scrubbing (20 seconds) physically wash away viruses and bacteria.\
Good personal hygiene: regular bathing keeps skin and hair clean; wearing clean\
clothes; brushing teeth and flossing remove germs from your mouth (which can cause\
illness or cavities).\
Keeping your environment clean helps too: cover your nose/mouth when coughing or\
sneezing, throw tissues away, and clean toys or phones regularly.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Why is it important to wash your hands after using the bathroom?\
How does cleaning a cut (with soap and water) help prevent infection?\
What germs are you avoiding by washing your hands befoe eating?\
More to Learn:\
Community hygiene: Stay home and rest if you\'92re very sick to avoid passing germs to others\
(especially important with contagious diseases).Hygiene myth: Bathing too often can dry out skin. Typically, a daily shower or bath and daily\
handwashing are ideal.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
What happens if you touch your eyes or mouth with dirty hands?\
How does hygiene relate to the immune system?\
Why do you think soap is better than just water for handwashing?
\fs51\fsmilli25995 24 | Allergies \'96 When the Body\
Overreacts
\fs21\fsmilli10995 This lesson explains allergies, which are special immune reactions. We describe allergies as\
cases when the immune system mistakenly sees something harmless (like pollen, pet dander,\
or certain foods) as a threat. We give examples of common allergies: sneezing at pollen (hay\
fever), itchy eyes from dust mites, or hives from peanut exposure. The lesson explains why\
symptoms happen: the body releases chemicals (like histamine) that cause sneezing, itching, or\
watery eyes. We stress that allergies are not contagious. Children learn that treatments (like\
antihistamine medicine or avoiding triggers) can help manage allergies.\
By the end, students will understand that allergies are caused by the immune system being too\
sensitive. They will recall that in an allergy the immune system reacts to certain substances\
(substances called allergens). They will know some allergy symptoms (sneezing, itching) and\
simple management (cleaning allergen from room, medicine). This lesson helps them\
differentiate colds (viral) from allergies (immune reaction).
\fs51\fsmilli25995 24 | Content
\fs21\fsmilli10995 Lesson 24: Allergies \'96 When the Body Overreacts\
Allergies happen when the immune system overreacts to a harmless substance (allergen) like\
pollen, pet dander, or certain foods. Normally, these things don\'92t hurt us, but in allergies our\
body treats them like dangerous invaders. The immune system creates special antibodies to\
fight the allergen. When exposed again, these antibodies cause symptoms. For example, if\
you\'92re allergic to pollen, breathing it in makes your immune system release histamine, causing\
sneezing and itchy eyes. Common allergens include dust mites, pollen, animal fur, or foods like\
peanuts. Allergies can make you sneeze, itch, or get a rash, but they are not contagious.\
They\'92re managed by avoiding the trigger or using medicine (like antihistamines) to block the\
reaction.\
Starter Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
What happens if someone allergic to peanut eats a peanut?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Can you have a cold? Or is it an allergy? What\'92s the difference?\
\uc0\u9679 \
If petting a cat makes your eyes itchy, what does that suggest?\
Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
When the immune system misidentifies a harmless substance as a threat, it produces\
antibodies to fight it. This causes allergy symptoms (sneezing, runny nose, hives, etc.).\
Histamine is a chemical released during an allergic reaction. It makes blood vessels\
swell, mucus form, and causes itching or swelling (e.g. watery eyes with pollen allergy).\
Allergic reactions range from mild (sneezing) to severe (anaphylaxis, which is\
life-threatening swelling, for example from a peanut allergy). Anaphylaxis requires\
immediate medical care (EpiPen, etc.).\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
How are allergies different from catching a cold? (Hint: allergies don\'92t spread\
person-to-person, and have triggers like pollen)\
Why do antihistamine medicines help with allergy symptoms?\
How can people find out what they are allergic to?More to Learn:\
Allergy management: Keep windows closed when pollen is high, clean your room to reduce\
dust, and read labels to avoid food allergens.\
Immune system note: Allergies mean the immune system is working (perhaps too well!),\
showing how it can sometimes make mistakes.\
Questions:\
\uc0\u9679 \
Why might someone outgrow an allergy or develop new ones?\
\uc0\u9679 \
Can an allergy go away on its own?\
\uc0\u9679 \
What precautions should a child with a severe allergy always take?
\fs51\fsmilli25995 25 | Asthma \'96 Breathing Difficulties
\fs21\fsmilli10995 This lesson is about asthma, a common lung condition. We explain that asthma makes it\
sometimes hard to breathe because the airways narrow. Britannica describes that during an\
asthma attack, the small tubes in the lungs tighten and swell, and fill with mucus, making\
breathing difficult. The lesson outlines typical symptoms: coughing, wheezing (a whistling\
sound), and feeling out of breath. We also talk about triggers: things that can bring on an attack,\
such as exercise, dust, pollen, or a cold. The lesson reassures that asthma can be managed\
