Key Points:\
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
\uc0\u9679 \
Donors: A living person can donate some organs (kidney, part of liver) if it\'92s safe for\
them. Organs from deceased donors (cadavers) include heart, lungs, liver, kidneys,\
pancreas. Organs must be matched (blood type, tissue type) to reduce rejection.\
Transplant surgery: The new organ replaces the failing one. For example, a patient\
without working kidneys can receive a healthy kidney and then produce urine again.\
Rejection and meds: The immune system usually fights off foreign tissues. To stop it,\
transplant patients take immunosuppressant drugs so the body accepts the organ.\
These must be taken carefully for life.\
