\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students learn about ways doctors look inside the body without surgery. We\
introduce imaging tools like X-rays and MRI as examples. We explain that X-ray uses a form of\
energy (radiation) to take a picture of the inside of the body. For example, an X-ray can show\
the bones inside a part of the body. We also mention (without heavy detail) that MRI uses\
magnets, and ultrasound uses sound waves, to create images of organs and tissues. The\
lesson emphasizes that these tools are safe and help doctors diagnose broken bones or\
illnesses. Students see that imaging is part of medical technology that doctors use to\
understand what\'92s happening inside our bodies without having to open them up.\
Afterward, learners will know that imaging is like taking a special \'93photo\'94 of the insides. They will\
remember that X-rays reveal bones. They will understand that imaging helps doctors see things\
like fractures, swallowed objects, or even babies before they are born. This lesson gives them a\
basic idea of modern medical tools that help doctors.
